    {
      "id": "Exercice_01",
      "title": "Exercise 1 (4 points)",
      "total_exercise_points": "4",
      "introduction_context": "We consider four processes P1, P2, P3, and P4. Each uses three semaphores A, B, and C (initialized to 1). The code for each process is given below:",
      "pseudocode": {
        "declarations": [
          "A = 1 ; B = 1 ; C = 1 ;"
        ],
        "processes": [
          {
            "name": "P1",
            "code": [
              "P(A); P(B); ...; V(B); V(A)"
            ]
          },
          {
            "name": "P2",
            "code": [
              "P(B); P(C); ...; V(C); V(B)"
            ]
          },
          {
            "name": "P3",
            "code": [
              "P(C); P(D); ...; V(D); V(C)"
            ]
          },
          {
            "name": "P4",
            "code": [
              "P(D); P(A); ...; V(A); V(D)"
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      "Question": [
        {
          "id": "a",
          "question_text": "Explain why a deadlock might occur.",
          "Solution": null,
          "level": "Conceptual"
        },
        {
          "id": "b",
          "question_text": "Draw the wait-for graph corresponding to this situation.",
          "Solution": null,
          "level": "Procedural"
        },
        {
          "id": "c",
          "question_text": "Propose a solution to avoid deadlock while preserving access to the same resources.",
          "Solution": null,
          "level": "Metacognitive"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
